The organisation had also not uploaded its members' musical works into the digitised National Rights Registry (NRR) database as required by the law.
“The funds belonging to the Society will be held secure until the shortfall is resolved to the satisfaction of KECOBO,” said board chair Mutuma Mathiu, adding that MCSK’s management has already been made aware of the decision.
This is not the first time MCSK is in the limelight for the wrong reasons. Last year, the organisation came under attack from Kenyan artistes and their fans after it was discovered that it offered Sh2,500 each to musicians as royalties.



